				</div>
				</div>
				<div class="elementor-element elementor-element-0c6f765 elementor-widget-divider--view-line elementor-widget elementor-widget-divider" data-id="0c6f765" data-element_type="widget" data-widget_type="divider.default">
				<div class="elementor-widget-container">
					<div class="elementor-divider">
			<span class="elementor-divider-separator">
						</span>
		</div>
				</div>
				</div>
						</div>
					</div>
		</div>
								</div>
					</div>
		</section>
				<div class="elementor-element elementor-element-442d5ca elementor-widget elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id="442d5ca" data-element_type="widget" data-widget_type="text-editor.default">
				<div class="elementor-widget-container">
								<div class="elementor-text-editor elementor-clearfix">
				<h3>FAQs When Preparing for Private Equity Investment</h3>					</div>
						</div>
				</div>
				<div class="elementor-element elementor-element-36326aa uael-faq-box-layout-yes align-at-left elementor-widget elementor-widget-uael-faq" data-id="36326aa" data-element_type="widget" data-widget_type="uael-faq.default">
				<div class="elementor-widget-container">
			
			<div id='uael-faq-wrapper-568' class="uael-faq-wrapper">
				<div class="uael-faq-container uael-faq-layout-accordion" data-layout="accordion" >
												<div id="uael-accordion-dcb4eba" class="uael-faq-accordion" role="tablist">
								<div class= "uael-accordion-title" aria-expanded="false" role="tab">
									<span class="uael-accordion-icon uael-accordion-icon-left">
										<span class="uael-accordion-icon-closed"><i class="fas fa-angle-right"></i></span>
										<span class="uael-accordion-icon-opened"><i class="fas fa-angle-up"></i></span>
									</span>
									<span class="uael-question-dcb4eba uael-question-span" tabindex="0" id="uael-faq-1">How long does it typically take to raise capital? </span>
								</div>
								<div class="uael-accordion-content" role="tabpanel">
									<span>
									<span><p>As with most questions in the investment world, the answer here is “it depends” — on factors including size of the business, minority/majority investment or full acquisition, and the quality and intensity of resources being allocated to the initiative.</p><p>Some rules of thumb, though, would be to expect between 500–1,000 hours dedicated to the capital-raising process (between the creation of materials, preparation of diligence information, developing an investor list, running a process, and transaction negotiations).</p></span>									</span>
								</div>
							</div>
														<div id="uael-accordion-052737d" class="uael-faq-accordion" role="tablist">
								<div class= "uael-accordion-title" aria-expanded="false" role="tab">
									<span class="uael-accordion-icon uael-accordion-icon-left">
										<span class="uael-accordion-icon-closed"><i class="fas fa-angle-right"></i></span>
										<span class="uael-accordion-icon-opened"><i class="fas fa-angle-up"></i></span>
									</span>
									<span class="uael-question-052737d uael-question-span" tabindex="0" id="uael-faq-2">What does an investment banker do? How is that different from an M&amp;A advisor?</span>
								</div>
								<div class="uael-accordion-content" role="tabpanel">
									<span>
									<span><p>Investment bankers serve as an intermediary between buyers and sellers — either via equity or debt transactions. In most cases, the majority of the incentive for an investment banker comes from a success fee. Investment bankers are most often not expected to create business plans for companies they represent, rather focus primarily on connecting buyers and sellers.</p></span>									</span>
								</div>
							</div>
														<div id="uael-accordion-8a2f40a" class="uael-faq-accordion" role="tablist">
								<div class= "uael-accordion-title" aria-expanded="false" role="tab">
									<span class="uael-accordion-icon uael-accordion-icon-left">
										<span class="uael-accordion-icon-closed"><i class="fas fa-angle-right"></i></span>
										<span class="uael-accordion-icon-opened"><i class="fas fa-angle-up"></i></span>
									</span>
									<span class="uael-question-8a2f40a uael-question-span" tabindex="0" id="uael-faq-3">How much do investment bankers charge?</span>
								</div>
								<div class="uael-accordion-content" role="tabpanel">
									<span>
									<span><p>There’s typically a minimum hurdle (industry standard is usually $1m) for investment bankers to take on a project. They work to secure financing (debt, equity, or a combination thereof) for transactions. </p></span>									</span>
								</div>
							</div>
														<div id="uael-accordion-48c7784" class="uael-faq-accordion" role="tablist">
								<div class= "uael-accordion-title" aria-expanded="false" role="tab">
									<span class="uael-accordion-icon uael-accordion-icon-left">
										<span class="uael-accordion-icon-closed"><i class="fas fa-angle-right"></i></span>
										<span class="uael-accordion-icon-opened"><i class="fas fa-angle-up"></i></span>
									</span>
									<span class="uael-question-48c7784 uael-question-span" tabindex="0" id="uael-faq-4">How much do M&amp;A advisors typically get paid? What kind of services to they provide? </span>
								</div>
								<div class="uael-accordion-content" role="tabpanel">
									<span>
									<span><p>M&amp;A advisors are typically more involved throughout the stages of a transaction, including — in varying levels of intensity — a readiness audit, business assessment, business plan development, in addition to roles of an investment banker.  M&amp;A advisors typically charge an upfront fee (covering the cost of preparing materials), a retainer fee (to cover active management of the sell-side process), and a success fee (upon the close of a transaction). In some cases, the upfront fee and/or retainer fee could be backed out of the success fee.</p></span>									</span>
								</div>
							</div>
														<div id="uael-accordion-195a0b6" class="uael-faq-accordion" role="tablist">
								<div class= "uael-accordion-title" aria-expanded="false" role="tab">
									<span class="uael-accordion-icon uael-accordion-icon-left">
										<span class="uael-accordion-icon-closed"><i class="fas fa-angle-right"></i></span>
										<span class="uael-accordion-icon-opened"><i class="fas fa-angle-up"></i></span>
									</span>
									<span class="uael-question-195a0b6 uael-question-span" tabindex="0" id="uael-faq-5">What are typical funding rounds for businesses? How long in between raises?</span>
								</div>
								<div class="uael-accordion-content" role="tabpanel">
									<span>
									<span><p>Investment rounds typically start with Friends &amp; Family (the earliest stage, so much that it’s not typically included in formal funding rounds), and move to Seed Funding (the first official funding stage). Seed participants most often include the founders of the business, friends/family, or venture capital investors. </p><p>Following the Seed Round is typically Series A (the time span between these rounds is usually somewhere around 18 months). Series A funding typically gets a business through 6­–24 months, depending on the industry, prior to a Series B round (and so on). </p></span>									</span>
								</div>
							</div>
														<div id="uael-accordion-9d354b9" class="uael-faq-accordion" role="tablist">
								<div class= "uael-accordion-title" aria-expanded="false" role="tab">
									<span class="uael-accordion-icon uael-accordion-icon-left">
										<span class="uael-accordion-icon-closed"><i class="fas fa-angle-right"></i></span>
										<span class="uael-accordion-icon-opened"><i class="fas fa-angle-up"></i></span>
									</span>
									<span class="uael-question-9d354b9 uael-question-span" tabindex="0" id="uael-faq-6">How does the process and approach vary between a capital raise and a full buyout?</span>
								</div>
								<div class="uael-accordion-content" role="tabpanel">
									<span>
									<span><p>There are nuances between a minority investment (&lt;50% ownership), majority investment (50%+ investment), and full buyout (100% acquisition). The process in preparing materials is relatively similar for each, as investors at any stake will be looking for a clear understanding of the business in which they are investing.</p><p>Majority investments and full acquisitions are most likely to include potential changes to management teams and controls of the business, whereas a minority investment allows the business owner to retain control over the company.</p></span>									</span>
								</div>
							</div>
														<div id="uael-accordion-e36e3ac" class="uael-faq-accordion" role="tablist">
								<div class= "uael-accordion-title" aria-expanded="false" role="tab">
									<span class="uael-accordion-icon uael-accordion-icon-left">
										<span class="uael-accordion-icon-closed"><i class="fas fa-angle-right"></i></span>
										<span class="uael-accordion-icon-opened"><i class="fas fa-angle-up"></i></span>
									</span>
									<span class="uael-question-e36e3ac uael-question-span" tabindex="0" id="uael-faq-7">What is the difference between venture capital and private equity?</span>
								</div>
								<div class="uael-accordion-content" role="tabpanel">
									<span>
									<span><p>While these terms are used often interchangeably, they are quite different. Venture capital providers are financing startup or small business that are expected to generate high (above average) returns. VC investments are often minority positions and are typically seen as inherently riskier than private equity, though they often see a higher return on investment as a reward. Private equity investors purchase an interest in later-stage (more established) companies that are not publicly traded. These investment levels are traditionally higher and can range from minority to majority stakes or full buyouts.</p></span>									</span>
								</div>
							</div>
														<div id="uael-accordion-9d1931c" class="uael-faq-accordion" role="tablist">
								<div class= "uael-accordion-title" aria-expanded="false" role="tab">
									<span class="uael-accordion-icon uael-accordion-icon-left">
										<span class="uael-accordion-icon-closed"><i class="fas fa-angle-right"></i></span>
										<span class="uael-accordion-icon-opened"><i class="fas fa-angle-up"></i></span>
									</span>
									<span class="uael-question-9d1931c uael-question-span" tabindex="0" id="uael-faq-8">Do I really need a business plan?</span>
								</div>
								<div class="uael-accordion-content" role="tabpanel">
									<span>
									<span><p>The short answer: yes. Investors, naturally, want to know what they are investing in — and a comprehensive business plan (not simply an Excel spreadsheet with straight-line projections) is often one of the best ways to communicate the opportunity and potential for a prospective investment.</p></span>									</span>
								</div>
							</div>
											</div>
			</div>
					</div>
				</div>
						</div>
					</div>
		</div>
								</div>
					</div>
		</section>
				<section class="elementor-section elementor-top-section elementor-element elementor-element-a5005ec elementor-section-boxed elementor-section-height-default elementor-section-height-default" data-id="a5005ec" data-element_type="section">
						<div class="elementor-container elementor-column-gap-default">
							<div class="elementor-row">
					<div class="elementor-column elementor-col-100 elementor-top-column elementor-element elementor-element-dfcde5d" data-id="dfcde5d" data-element_type="column">
			<div class="elementor-column-wrap elementor-element-populated">
							<div class="elementor-widget-wrap">
						<div class="elementor-element elementor-element-9c375bb elementor-widget-divider--view-line elementor-widget elementor-widget-divider" data-id="9c375bb" data-element_type="widget" data-widget_type="divider.default">
				<div class="elementor-widget-container">
					<div class="elementor-divider">
			<span class="elementor-divider-separator">
						</span>
		</div>
				</div>
				</div>
